EmpathoSense: An Ideal Brain‚ÄìHeart Imaging Modality for Empathy

by Alicia O.

üìÑ This portfolio is a self-contained HTML document with all images embedded. Contains 8 images extracted from PDF. Videos require Google Drive access to play.

Introduction

My ideal brain imaging technology is to capture what we call human empathy. Instead of relying on the phrase ‚ÄúI‚Äôm an empath‚Äù, this technology would measure biological mechanisms like neural firing, blood flow, and autonomic regulation that make up the empathic response. Empathy is not just ‚Äúfeeling with‚Äù another person; it‚Äôs a scientific coordinated dance between brain circuits for social understanding and body signals like heartbeat and breathing. Contemporary neuroimaging has shown that empathy recruits distributed networks in the medial prefrontal cortex, temporoparietal junction (TPJ), cingulate cortex, and sensory areas that support mirroring and mentalizing (Lian et al., 2025). At the same time, interoceptive signals from the heart and autonomic nervous system shape how strongly we respond to others‚Äô emotions (Lischke et al., 2017).

Based on the lecture content, current methods capture parts of this system: EEG can track fast mirroring-related activity, fNIRS and fMRI track slower hemodynamic changes, and photoplethysmography (PPG) or ECG measure heart rate and heart rate variability (HRV). But they are often bulky, lab-bound, or focused on a single body system. The ideal empathy-imaging modality would be wearable and comfortable in natural social situations. It would measure both fast neural dynamics (milliseconds) and slower hemodynamics (seconds). Simultaneously record cardiac signals and brain activity from two interacting people. Provide interpretable features linked to empathy, such as mu rhythm suppression, interpersonal neural synchrony, and brain‚Äìheart coupling.

Building on EEG, optical neuroimaging (fNIRS/EROS), and PPG concepts lecture, this paper imagines EmpathoSense, a next-generation brain‚Äìheart imaging technique optimized for empathy research. EmpathoSense is explicitly multimodal. It combines EEG, time-resolved optical imaging, and cardiac sensing into one integrated system, designed around known markers of empathy. Cortical mirroring and affect sharing (EEG) EEG records scalp potentials generated by synchronized postsynaptic activity in large populations of pyramidal neurons.

EEG and Mu Rhythm Suppression

For empathy, the key signal is mu rhythm suppression (8‚Äì13 Hz) over the sensorimotor cortex. When individuals observe or imagine others‚Äô actions or emotions, oscillations in the mu band decrease; this has been interpreted as a signature of engagement in the mirror neuron system and ‚Äúexperience sharing‚Äù (Hobson & Bishop, 2016). Recent work shows that mu suppression during emotional facial expressions and social scenes tracks individual differences in empathy (Hung et al., 2024).

EmpathoSense would therefore include: High-density EEG over central and frontal areas (e.g., C3/Cz/C4, inferior frontal sites) using a 10‚Äì20‚Äìcompatible dry electrode array. Real-time estimation of mu and beta power (8‚Äì30 Hz) and event-related potentials (ERPs) in response to others‚Äô pain, sadness, or joy. These features provide millisecond-resolution indices of how quickly a person‚Äôs brain ‚Äúresonates‚Äù with another‚Äôs state.

Optical Imaging and fNIRS

To complement EEG, EmpathoSense uses time-resolved near-infrared spectroscopy (TR-fNIRS) and EROS-style scattering measurements over key social brain regions: Medial and dorsolateral prefrontal cortex, Temporoparietal junction (TPJ), and Superior temporal sulcus (STS). Conventional fNIRS measures changes in oxy- and deoxyhemoglobin as a slow hemodynamic proxy of neural activity (Baz√°n & Amaro Jr., 2022). Emerging time-domain fNIRS and EROS systems go further by measuring photon time-of-flight to separate superficial and deep signals and detect subtle scattering changes tied to neural activity on sub-second scales (Czeszumski et al., 2020).

Empathy and real-time social interaction are associated with increased activation and interpersonal neural synchrony in these cortical areas, especially when people cooperate or share emotions (Konrad et al., 2024). EmpathoSense would leverage this idea by delivering picosecond light pulses at multiple near-infrared wavelengths (760/850 nm). Recording arrival-time distributions of photons with single-photon detectors to derive both the standard fNIRS measures of Œî[HbO] and Œî[HbR]. Fast scattering-based signals similar to EROS, capturing rapid local tissue changes during neural firing. This dual optical channel provides both where in the social brain empathy is engaged and how its activity evolves over hundreds of milliseconds.

Cardiac Monitoring and Interoception

Empathy is tightly linked to interoception, our ability to sense internal bodily states. Higher heart-rate variability (especially high-frequency HRV) is associated with better recognition of others‚Äô emotional states and more successful social relationships (Lischke et al., 2017). EmpathoSense would thus continuously record: PPG signals from the forehead (integrated into the headband) and optionally from the finger, using dual-wavelength LEDs similar to pulse oximeters. ECG from chest or behind-the-ear electrodes for better R-peak timing.

Derived measures would be the Instantaneous heart rate and HRV (time and frequency domain)‚Äîheartbeat-evoked potentials in EEG, indexing cortical processing of cardiac signals. Cardiac-respiratory coupling and its modulation during empathic engagement. By synchronizing these cardiac measures with brain activity, the system can probe how body-state sensitivity amplifies or dampens empathic responses.

Hyperscanning and Interpersonal Synchrony

Empathosense would also rely on Inter-brain and brain‚Äìheart synchrony (hyperscanning). A key innovation is that EmpathoSense is designed for hyperscanning: simultaneous recording from two interacting people. Hyperscanning studies using EEG and fNIRS show that cooperation, emotional sharing, and close relationships are accompanied by interpersonal neural synchrony (INS), correlated activity between brains (Lian et al., 2025).

EmpathoSense builds directly on the EEG signal chain and optical imaging hardware introduced lecture, with a wearable headset design in which each participant wears a lightweight headset that integrates 32-channel dry EEG using a 10‚Äì20 layout over frontal, central, and temporoparietal regions. An array of near-infrared sources and detectors (short and long source‚Äìdetector separations) embedded in flexible ‚Äúoptode pods,‚Äù inspired by modern high-density fNIRS caps and systems like NIRSport 2 and Muse S Athena (Baz√°n & Amaro Jr., 2022). Optionally, a chest ECG patch communicates wirelessly with the headset.

The data stream in real time to a tablet or laptop running a BrainImation-like environment for visualization and BCI-style feedback. Hyperscanning is achieved by synchronizing two headsets to a shared clock and exchanging timing pulses over Bluetooth or Wi-Fi.

Conclusion and Future Directions

EmpathoSense data are inherently multidimensional. A typical empathy experiment (e.g., watching videos of someone in pain or in danger vs. neutral scenes, or engaging in a cooperative game) would produce EEG time‚Äìfrequency maps, Optical activation maps, Cardiac HRV traces and Interpersonal synchrony metrics. Mu and beta power over the sensorimotor cortex drop during observation of others‚Äô pain (mu suppression). Frontal theta or gamma bursts during perspective-taking or cognitive empathy tasks (Genzer et al., 2022). fNIRS Œî[HbO]/Œî[HbR] topographies over prefrontal and TPJ regions, showing increased activation during emotional perspective-taking. EROS-like fast-scattering signals reveal rapid, transient responses that align with key moments in social interaction. Heart rate time series showing phasic accelerations or decelerations in response to emotional stimuli (Lischke et al.). Cross-correlation between one partner‚Äôs HRV and the other‚Äôs neural markers of empathy, probing ‚Äúheart-to-brain‚Äù coupling.

Overall, the EEG in EmpathoSense relies on the same physical principles described in lecture: synchronized postsynaptic potentials in cortical pyramidal neurons generate electric fields that propagate through brain, skull, and scalp, where they are detected as microvolt-level potentials. The system‚Äôs high temporal resolution (millisecond scale) makes it ideal for detecting rapid changes in mu rhythm and ERPs linked to empathic processing. Heartbeat-evoked potentials in EEG index cortical processing of cardiac afferent signals; their magnitude relates to interoceptive awareness and to activity in empathy-related networks (Ernst et al., 2012).

Even as an ‚Äúideal‚Äù modality, EmpathoSense faces constraints. The interpretation of ‚Äúempathy‚Äù, neural markers like mu suppression or prefrontal activation are correlates, not direct measures of empathy. In terms of generalizability, Machine learning models trained on limited populations may not generalize across cultures, ages, or neurodivergent groups. Physiological baselines and HRV norms vary widely, so ‚Äúlow empathy‚Äù in one person might simply reflect different autonomic traits.

These limitations highlight that even an idealized EmpathoSense system must be paired with cautious interpretation, but it is a good starting point to go further on empathetic research. In practice, such a system would not read minds or deliver a single ‚Äúempathy score.‚Äù Instead, it would provide a nuanced set of signals, mu suppression, prefrontal activation, HRV, and cross-brain synchrony that researchers and clinicians could use to better understand how people connect, care, and sometimes fail to do so. As consumer-grade EEG‚ÄìfNIRS headsets and wearable PPG devices continue to evolve, elements of EmpathoSense may move from science fiction toward everyday tools for mental health, education, and social neuroscience.

// üßò Meditation Garden ‚Äî Neurofeedback Training Tool
// Responds to EEG alpha (relaxation), attention (focus), and theta (deep calm).
// Requirements covered: real-time EEG access, substantial features, polished visuals, comments, simulation fallback.
// ----------- CONFIG -----------
const NUM_FLOWERS = 7;
const GARDEN_MARGIN = 80;
const SMOOTH = 0.08; // lerp smoothing for stable UX
const MAX_PETALS = 12;
let flowers = [];
let fireflies = [];
let hudFontSize = 14;
// Smoothed EEG values (so visuals don‚Äôt jitter)
let sAlpha = 0, sAttention = 0, sTheta = 0;
// Optional: enable subtle grain for polish
let t = 0;
// Simulation fallback if eegData not available in environment
function getEEG() {
if (typeof eegData !== "undefined" && eegData) return eegData;
// ---- SIMULATION MODE ----
// Moves slowly & smoothly; tweak to demo different states in video.
const sim = {
alpha: 0.55 + 0.35 * sin(frameCount * 0.007) + 0.05 * noise(frameCount * 0.005),
attention: 0.5 + 0.4 * sin(frameCount * 0.011 + 2) + 0.05 * noise(frameCount * 0.009),
theta: 0.45 + 0.4 * sin(frameCount * 0.006 + 5),
delta: 0.3 + 0.2 * noise(frameCount * 0.004),
beta: 0.35 + 0.3 * sin(frameCount * 0.013),
meditation: null // not used directly
};
// Clamp 0..1
for (let k of ["alpha", "attention", "theta", "delta", "beta"]) {
sim[k] = constrain(sim[k], 0, 1);
}
return sim;
}
function setup() {
// BrainImation typically creates the canvas; if not, you can uncomment:
// createCanvas(960, 540);
colorMode(HSB, 360, 100, 100, 1);
noStroke();
textFont("ui-monospace, Menlo, Consolas, monospace");
textSize(hudFontSize);
// Initialize flowers on a pleasing grid
for (let i = 0; i < NUM_FLOWERS; i++) {
const x = map(i, 0, NUM_FLOWERS - 1, GARDEN_MARGIN, width - GARDEN_MARGIN);
const y = height - random(140, 220);
flowers.push(new Flower(x, y));
}
}
function draw() {
const eeg = getEEG();
// Smooth EEG for stability
sAlpha = lerp(sAlpha, eeg.alpha ?? 0, SMOOTH);
sAttention = lerp(sAttention, eeg.attention ?? 0, SMOOTH);
sTheta = lerp(sTheta, eeg.theta ?? 0, SMOOTH);
// Background: hue shifts with alpha; brightness lifts with theta
const bgHue = map(sAlpha, 0, 1, 200, 300); // blue ‚Üí purple
const bgBri = map(sTheta, 0, 1, 15, 28); // darker ‚Üí slightly brighter
background(bgHue, 45, bgBri, 1);
// Subtle ground gradient
drawGround();
// Update + draw flowers
for (let f of flowers) {
f.update(sAlpha, sAttention);
f.display();
}
// Fireflies increase with theta (calm = dreamy particles)
maybeSpawnFireflies(sTheta);
updateFireflies();
// HUD overlay
drawHUD(eeg);
// Optional grain for polish
t += 0.005;
// addGrain(12, 0.015); // uncomment for film grain
}
// ----------- CLASSES -----------
class Flower {

constructor(x, y) {
this.x = x;
this.y = y;
this.stemH = random(90, 140);
this.petalSeed = random(1000);
this.coreSize = random(18, 28);
this.baseHue = random(0, 360);
this.size = random(28, 40);
this.petalCount = floor(random(6, MAX_PETALS));
this.jitter = 0; // reduced by attention
}
update(alpha, attention) {
// Grow with alpha (relaxation)
const growth = map(alpha, 0, 1, 0.9, 1.9);
this.size = lerp(this.size, 28 * growth + 40 * growth, 0.07);
// Stabilize petals with attention (focus)
const jitterTarget = map(attention, 0, 1, 0.9, 0.1);
this.jitter = lerp(this.jitter, jitterTarget, 0.08);
// Color shifts with alpha (so calm = warmer petals)
this.hue = (this.baseHue + map(alpha, 0, 1, -20, 60)) % 360;
this.sat = map(alpha, 0, 1, 45, 85);
this.bri = map(alpha, 0, 1, 70, 100);
}
display() {
push();
translate(this.x, this.y);
// Stem
push();
stroke(120, 50, 50);
strokeWeight(3);
line(0, 0, 0, -this.stemH);
pop();
// Blossom
translate(0, -this.stemH);
noStroke();
// Petals
const r = this.size;
for (let i = 0; i < this.petalCount; i++) {
const a = (TWO_PI * i) / this.petalCount;
const j = (noise(frameCount * 0.01 + this.petalSeed + i) - 0.5) * this.jitter * 12;
const px = (r + j) * cos(a);
const py = (r + j) * sin(a);
fill(this.hue, this.sat, this.bri, 0.85);
ellipse(px, py, r * 0.9, r * 0.55);
}
// Core
fill((this.hue + 40) % 360, 65, 95, 0.95);
ellipse(0, 0, this.coreSize, this.coreSize);
pop();
}
}
class Firefly {
constructor() {
this.x = random(width);
this.y = random(height * 0.25, height * 0.85);
this.vx = random(-0.4, 0.4);
this.vy = random(-0.2, 0.2);
this.a = random(TWO_PI);
this.r = random(1.5, 3.2);
this.h = random(40, 80);
}
update() {
this.a += 0.02;
this.x += this.vx + 0.4 * sin(this.a);
this.y += this.vy + 0.3 * cos(this.a * 0.8);
if (this.x < 0) this.x = width;
if (this.x > width) this.x = 0;
if (this.y < 0) this.y = height;
if (this.y > height) this.y = 0;
}
display() {
const blink = 0.6 + 0.4 * sin(frameCount * 0.1 + this.a);
fill(55, 90, 100, blink);
ellipse(this.x, this.y, this.r * 2, this.r * 2);
}
}

function drawGround() {
const h1 = 120, s1 = 30, b1 = 22;
const h2 = 120, s2 = 45, b2 = 28;
noStroke();

function maybeSpawnFireflies(theta) {
// More theta ‚Üí more fireflies
const targetCount = floor(map(theta, 0, 1, 5, 32));
if (fireflies.length < targetCount && random() < 0.2) {
fireflies.push(new Firefly());
} else if (fireflies.length > targetCount && random() < 0.1) {
fireflies.pop();
}
}
function updateFireflies() {
for (let f of fireflies) {
f.update();
f.display();
}
}
// Optional film grain (subtle polish)
function addGrain(density = 10, alpha = 0.02) {
for (let i = 0; i < width * density; i++) {
const x = random(width), y = random(height);
fill(0, 0, 100, alpha * random(0.5, 1));
rect(x, y, 1, 1);
}
}

Part 1:
BCI: is a Brain-Computer Interface, a system that translates brain activity into commands to
control technology. It works by capturing neural signals, interpreting them, and transforming
them into commands for external devices, allowing for a direct communication link between the
brain and a computer without using the body's normal neuromuscular pathways. This is a
technology that is often used to restore function for individuals with disabilities or to explore how
the brain works.
For this midterm, extend your Assignment 2 work by implementing a novel BCI concept that
goes beyond simple "brain waves control visual parameters."

Brief explanation of the part 1 game:
This EEG driven walking in Heels React game üë† that maps brain waves
(alpha/beta/theta/gamma) to attention, stress, and activation, and uses those to control a girl
walking in heels in which walk speed ramps up when she‚Äôs relaxed (high alpha), and slows
when stressed. The difficulty also auto-adapts in which high attention/stress ‚Üí fewer obstacles
(easier) and low attention/stress ‚Üí more obstacles (harder). Auto-jump triggers when the brain
is ‚Äúmost active‚Äù (activation spike / very high beta), and you can still press the space bar to jump.
Ideally this would work best to connect with real time EEG brain data but for the purpose of the
demo it uses simulated data.
I used the help of AI to generate the code for my specific requests and entered it into the
sandbox react to visualize it. At first it came up with a very simple game, after many errors and
requests I was able to go from this basic one (picture below on the left) to a more girl and
colorful one in which I could adjust the skin-tone to better customize the character to represent
whoever would hypothetically use it (picture on the right)!

3
Overall, this project demonstrates a novel Brain-Computer Interface (BCI) concept that
dynamically adapts game difficulty and behavior to maintain an ideal ‚Äúflow state.‚Äù Instead of
simply mapping EEG signals to basic on/off commands or fixed parameters, it builds a
continuous feedback loop between simulated brain activity and game mechanics creating an
adaptive, emotionally aware environment in a background of pretty sunset clouds.
The BCI model simulates four major brainwave bands (alpha, beta, theta, gamma) that
correspond to relaxation, focus, drowsiness, and cognitive activation. These waves are
translated into higher-level cognitive indicators: attention, stress, and activation. These
indicators drive the closed-loop system that adjusts gameplay in real time, when attention or
stress rises, the system interprets that as mental overload and automatically reduces difficulty
(fewer obstacles, slower pace). When the player relaxes or loses focus, the challenge gradually
increases to re-engage attention. This continuous balancing act helps keep the player in an
‚Äúoptimal‚Äù zone of engagement. Unlike basic parameter control where EEG merely toggles a
variable or changes color, this implementation uses multi-dimensional signal interpretation and
contextual responses. The game doesn‚Äôt just react, but it predicts and adapts. The EEG data
modulates the environmental complexity, motion speed, and even the character‚Äôs ‚Äúenergy‚Äù
through an intelligent mapping that mirrors neurofeedback training principles. The experience of
coming up with this game reinforced that future BCI-driven interfaces can go beyond control to
create emotionally responsive systems, where technology adjusts to our cognitive state instead
of forcing us to adapt to it.

Brief explanation of the part 2 ERP:
This experiment was designed to measure a classic event-related potential (ERP) component
associated with cognitive evaluation and attention: the P300 (or P3b). The P300 is typically
elicited using an oddball paradigm where participants detect infrequent, task-relevant stimuli
among frequent, non-target ones. It usually appears as a positive deflection peaking around 300
ms after stimulus onset, strongest over centro-parietal scalp sites, and reflects processes of
context updating and attentional resource allocation.
In this study, the visual stimuli are cat-themed analogues of the traditional circle/annulus task.
Each trial begins with a filled black circle (the ‚Äúcat face‚Äù) for 30 ms, followed by a 60 ms blank
interval and then a circular annulus (‚Äúcat paw ring‚Äù) for 30 ms. The standard condition (80%)
displays a grey cat, while the oddball condition (20%) shows a golden cat. Stimuli appear once
every second, creating a continuous and rhythmic presentation resembling early EEG averaging
machines from the 1970s.
At each stimulus onset, a ‚àí200 ms to +800 ms EEG epoch is captured from the Muse headset‚Äôs
four channels (TP9, AF7, AF8, TP10). Each epoch is baseline-corrected using the pre-stimulus
interval (‚àí200‚Äì0 ms) and stored separately for standard and oddball trials. The program

5
computes running averages across up to 60 trials per condition, displaying both averaged
waveforms simultaneously for direct comparison.
Based on the literature, if tested with real EEG data, I would expect the oddball (gold cat) stimuli
to elicit a larger P300 amplitude around 300‚Äì500 ms relative to the standard grey cats. Earlier
sensory components such as N100 or P200 might also appear, reflecting initial visual
processing. The averaged traces should reveal these characteristic ERP differences once
sufficient trials are collected, illustrating the neural signature of selective attention and novelty
detection!
